            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "\"Secondary agent\" can mean different things depending on the system, but commonly it’s an auxiliary or supporting agent that complements a primary agent. Typical capabilities and roles:\n\nCore capabilities\n- Execute specialized subtasks: run specific tools, fetch external data, call APIs, generate formatted outputs.\n- Background/long-running work: perform tasks that take time (indexing, batch processing, retries).\n- Monitoring and alerting: watch metrics, detect failures, send alerts or triggers.\n- Validation and QA: verify or filter primary agent outputs (consistency checks, safety filters).\n- Error handling and retries: handle transient failures, retry logic, fallbacks.\n- State, caching, and persistence: keep context, caches, or logs used by primary agent.\n- Orchestration and coordination: break a large job into steps, manage workflows, delegate to other agents.\n- Escalation and human-in-the-loop: decide when to escalate to a human or to the primary agent.\n- Access-controlled actions: hold different privileges (e.g., read-only vs write) for safer operation.\n\nInteraction patterns\n- Synchronous helper: called on-demand by the primary agent and returns results immediately.\n- Asynchronous worker: receives tasks via a queue/event and processes them independently.\n- Observer/monitor: passively observes events and only acts on triggers.\n- Peer collaborator: two agents exchange responsibilities and negotiate task ownership.\n\nExample uses by domain\n- Customer support: primary handles initial chat, secondary runs account lookups, executes refunds, or runs diagnostics.\n- Search/assistant: primary converses; secondary performs web searches, runs code execution, or summarizes long documents.\n- Robotics: primary plans motion; secondary handles sensor fusion, localization, or safety checks.\n- Software automation: primary composes instructions; secondary executes API calls, deploys code, or runs tests.\n\nLimitations and considerations\n- Permissions and security: give the secondary only the privileges it needs.\n- Observability: log decisions and actions for auditing.\n- Latency: balance background work vs user-facing responsiveness.\n- Reliability: design retries, backoff and fallbacks for critical tasks.\n- Clear handoffs: define what the primary should vs shouldn’t do to avoid duplicated work.\n\nIf you mean a specific \"secondary agent\" in a particular product, architecture, or use case, tell me which one and I’ll describe its exact functions and how to configure it.",
